The Young’s modulus of the cranium is much higher than that of brain tissue.19,46 Still, in a contact loading situation of the head the deformation of the skull is important, because it initiates strain waves in the brain tissue. In this study, however, only inertial loading of the head is considered and therefore the cranium is assumed to be rigid. The cranium is incorporated in the boundary condition at Γ3. Because of the low shear modulus of the CSF, the influence of the rigid constraint associated with the cranium at boundary Γ3 in the x-direction can be neglected. Provided no rotation of the model occurs, the constraint equation for all nodes on boundary Γ3 is8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}$$ v|_{\Upgamma_{3}} = v_{\rm s} $$\end{document}with vs the vertical displacement of the skull.

